MODEL #3: Polynomial models

Part A

#Fit a quadratic model using Age to predict Price and examine the residuals. Give the prediction equation and show a scatterplot of the data with the quadratic fit drawn on it.

model3a=lm(Price~poly(Age,degree=2, raw=TRUE), data=MyCars)

Residual Analysis:

Based on the fitted values vs residuals plot seem to be distributed evenly around the horizontal reference line. There is a little bit of fanning that occurs as the fitted values increase, but it seems realitively linear. Because the residuals are seemingly equally distributed around the reference line this also implies that there is zero mean. Residuals seem to be scattered around 0 implying constant variance of the residuals. There is a little right-skew in the frequency of the residuals as seen in the histogram, however this is relatively tame. The tails of the QQ plot deviate a little from the diagonal reference line but are generally independent and seem normally distributed. I would have checked normality using sapply() however the output would have been too massive to really check.

Part B

Null Hypothesis: H0: βAge = βAge^2 =0

Alternative Hypothesis: Ha: βAge + βAge^2≠0

#Perform a hypothesis test to determine if this model is significant. List your hypotheses, p-value, and conclusion.

anova455(model3a)

Using anova455() we can determine that the model created in part A is significant. This is because our p-value is < 2.2e-16 which is effectively 0. Beacuse of this we can reject the null hypothesis.

Part C

#You are looking at a 3-year-old car of your model and want to find an interval that is likely to contain its Price using your quadratic model. Construct an interval predict the value of this car, and include an interpretive sentence in context.

newx = data.frame(Age=3)
predict.lm(model3a, newx, interval = "prediction", level=0.95)
##        fit      lwr      upr
## 1 16451.17 11742.39 21159.96

The prediction interval is saying that we expect a unique, three year old Honda Accord to cost between 11742.39 and 21159.96 USD. The prediction interval is wider than the confidence interval because there is an extra 1 added to the denominator term in the calculation. This extra 1 is necessary in the prediction interval becuase it is harder to predict one value as opposed to an entire population’s average value.

Part D

#Does the quadratic model allow for some Age where a car has a zero or negative predicted price? Justify your answer using a calculation or graph.

plot(Price~Age,main="Quadratic Model",data=MyCars)
curve(b0.model3a+b1.model3a*x+b2.model3a*x^2,add=TRUE)

Based on the above graph, we cannot have a car with some unique Age where the price would be zero or negative. This is due to the quadratic nature of the graph. Nowhere in the above graph does the line dip below the x-axis which means we have fixed the problem in the HW2 model where at a certain age, the price of the car would be predicted to be 0 USD.

Part E

#What happens in the quadratic model for cars that are very old? Can you think of a plausible “real world” explanation for this- or is it a flaw of the quadratic model?

OldCars = MyCars[MyCars$Age>11,]
count(OldCars)

Again, looking at the graph, we see that the predicted price of a car based on its age starts to plateau when age approaches and surpasses 11. I think there are two factors to explain this: the first being that after a certain age, cars just aren’t that valuable anymore. They have some value if they run, but the difference between an 11 year old car and a 12 or 13 year old car isn’t that much. Any of those cars are still considered old and of little value. Another reason is that only 8 of the 200 cars in the data set are older than 11 years old. Because of this it is hard to predict these values as well as cars with lower age values. In short, I think cars after a certain age have little value that likely plataeus in the real world, and my model has few high age values to predict price for older cars.

Although all of the models appear to fit the data well, once we look at the summary outputs we can see which predictors are and aren’t significant in the model. Looking at the sumamry output for model3fQuadratic, all the predictors are highly significant. Looking at the summary output for model3fCubic, 3 of the 4 predictors are significant but the cubic term isn’t (p = 0.15870). Looking at the summary output of model3fQuartic, only two of the predictors were significant. The significant predictors only the constant term and the linear term. The quadratic, cubic, and quartic terms were all insignificant with p values of (p = 0.189, 0.554, and 0.684) respectively. Becuase the cubic and quartic models had insignificant predictors, this suggests that both of these models overfit the data, and are unnecessarily complex.

MODEL #4: Complete second order model

Part A

#Fit a complete second order model for predicting a used car Price based on Age and Mileage and examine the residuals.
#Include interaction term

model4a=lm(Price~Age+Mileage+I(Age^2)+I(Mileage^2)+I(Age*Mileage),data=MyCars)
summary(model4a)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = Price ~ Age + Mileage + I(Age^2) + I(Mileage^2) + 
##     I(Age * Mileage), data = MyCars)
## 
## Residuals:
##    Min     1Q Median     3Q    Max 
##  -4826  -1383   -360   1236   8168 
## 
## Coefficients:
##                    Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)       2.357e+04  3.970e+02  59.365  < 2e-16 ***
## Age              -1.779e+03  2.311e+02  -7.699 6.83e-13 ***
## Mileage          -6.264e-02  1.641e-02  -3.817 0.000181 ***
## I(Age^2)          5.194e+01  2.696e+01   1.926 0.055523 .  
## I(Mileage^2)      8.462e-08  1.946e-07   0.435 0.664243    
## I(Age * Mileage)  1.990e-03  4.291e-03   0.464 0.643302    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

## Multiple R-squared:  0.819,  Adjusted R-squared:  0.8143 
## F-statistic: 175.6 on 5 and 194 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16
plot(model4a$residuals~model4a$fitted.values, main="Raw Residuals vs Fitted Values", data=MyCars)
abline(0,0)

hist(model4a$residuals)

qqnorm(model4a$residuals)
qqline(model4a$residuals)

plot(model4a)

Residual Analysis:

Based on the fitted values vs residuals plot seem to be distributed evenly around the horizontal reference line. There is some fanning of the residuals as the fitted values increase but overall it looks decently linear. Because the residuals are seemingly equally distributed around the reference line this also implies that there is zero mean and there is constant variance. There is a little right-skew, although less than MODEL 3, in the frequency of the residuals as seen in the histogram, however this is relatively tame seeing as few data sets fit the normal curve perfectly. The tails of the QQ plot deviate a little from the diagonal reference line but are generally independent and seem normally distributed. The right tail deviates more than the left one, and is due to the right skew in the data. I would have checked normality using sapply() however the output would have been too massive to really check.

Part B

Null Hypothesis: H0: βAge = βAge^2 = βMileage = βMileage^2 = βAge*Mileage=0

Alternative Hypothesis: Ha: βAge + βAge^2 +βMileage + βMileage^2 + βAge*Mileage≠0

anova455(model4a)

Using anova455() we can determine that the model created in part A is significant. This is because our p-value is < 2.2e-16 which is effectively 0. Beacuse of this we can reject the null hypothesis. I used anova455() instead of anova() because we want to see if the overall model is significant, not individual predictors.

Part C

Null Hypothesis: H0: βAge^2 = βMileage^2 = βAge*Mileage=0

Alternative Hypothesis: Ha: βAge^2 + βMileage^2 + βAge*Mileage≠0

#Reduced model leaves out predictors you are testing
model4c = lm(Price~Age+Mileage, data=MyCars)
anova(model4c,model4a)

Using anova() to compare the reduced model (model4c) with the original model (model4a) we see that the nested F test tells us that at least one of the predictors we are interested in is significant (p-value = 1.087e-08) and should be included in the model. We should reject the null hypothesis.

Part D

Null Hypothesis: H0: βMileage = βMileage^2 = βAge*Mileage=0

Alternative Hypothesis: Ha: βMileage + βMileage^2 + βAge*Mileage≠0

model4d = lm(Price~Age + I(Age^2),data=MyCars)
anova(model4d, model4a)

Using anova() to compare the reduced model (model4d) with the original model (model4a) we see that the nested F test tells us that at least one of the predictors we are interested in is significant (p-value = 3.36e-05) and should be included in the model. We should reject the null hypothesis.

Part D

Null Hypothesis: H0: βModel = β(Age*Model) = β(Mileage*Model)=0

Alternative Hypothesis: Ha: βModel + β(Age*Model) + β(Mileage*Model)≠0

#Perform a hypothesis test to determine the importance of Model terms in the model constructed in part C). List your hypotheses, p-value, and conclusion.

model5d = lm(Price~Age+Mileage, data=Escape)
anova(model5d,model5c)

Using anova() to compare the reduced model (model5d) with the original model (model5c) we see that the nested F test tells us that Model is significant (p-value = 2.105e-07) and should be included in the model. We should reject the null hypothesis.

Part E

The main difference between the model constructed in part A (without interaction terms) and part C (with interaction terms). Without the interaction terms all you can do with a model is change where its y-intercept is and shift it up and down the y axis. With the interaction terms, you can also control the slope of the line predicting our data. We should use the model with the interaction terms since we can better fit our line to our data.
